":[{"name":"Bevil","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Bevill  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beville","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Surrey; of Norman origin): variant of   Bovill  . Derivation from Beuville (Calvados) is also possible, though unproven.","French (also <b>Béville</b>): habitational name from Béville (Moselle) or Béville-le-Comte (Eure-et-Loir), or a variant of <b>Beuville</b>, a habitational name from Beuville (Calvados). The surname <i>Béville</i> is rare in France."]},{"name":"Bevel","meanings":["English (Devon): of Norman origin, a variant of   Bevill  ."]},{"name":"Bevels","meanings":["English: variant of   Bevill  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"],"variants":[{"name":"Maud","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilda Bevill was born in 1327, in Sherford, Devon, England, United Kingdom. She married David Hals in 1348, in Sherford, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1417, in Lelant, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1327–after 1417":"1327–pärast 1417","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1349–1417":"1349–1417","1351–1417":"1351–1417","1327–1417":"1327–1417","23 February 1417":"23. veebruar 1417","1351":"1351","Aft 1405":"pärast 1405","Abt 1417":"umbes 1417","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1348":"1348","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1323":"1323","after 1417":"pärast 1417","1417":"1417","about 1351":"umbes 1351","1405":"1405","Lelant, Saint Ives, Cornwall, England":"Lelant, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kennedon Farm, Sherford, Devonshire, England":"Sherford, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lelant, Cornwall, England":"Lelant, Cornwall, England","Lavant, Sussex, England":"Lavant, Sussex, England","Kenedon Manor, Sherford, Devon, England":"Sherford, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1327–after 1417":"1327–1417 jälkeen","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1349–1417":"1349–1417","1351–1417":"1351–1417","1327–1417":"1327–1417","23 February 1417":"23. helmikuuta 1417","1351":"1351","Aft 1405":"1405 jälkeen","Abt 1417":"noin 1417","1327":"1327","1349":"1349","1348":"1348","about 1349":"noin 1349","1323":"1323","after 1417":"1417 jälkeen","1417":"1417","about 1351":"noin 1351","1405":"1405","Lelant, Saint Ives, Cornwall, England":"Lelant, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kenned